California Central Valley

The California Central Valley, stretching from Redding to Bakersfield, spans almost 18 thousand square miles and is characterized by flat, extensively cultivated plains. The valley is divided in two: the Sacramento Valley and the San Joaquin Valley. Both have river systems which meet at the Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta and drain into the San Francisco Bay.

The Central Valley experiences hot, dry summers and mild winters, with an annual rainfall ranging from 5 to 25 inches. The region once had prairies, oak savannas, desert grasslands, riparian woodlands, freshwater marshes, and vernal pools, but due to the extremely fertile soil, over half is now dedicated to cropland. The extensive cropland has posed a problem for various native bird species, including greater and lesser sandhill cranes, waterfowl, shorebirds who relied on the wetlands of the valley.

Due to the growing population of California, more people have begun migrating into cities in the region, such as Sacramento, Fresno, Modesto, and Bakersfield. Notable areas and landmarks within this region are the Sacramento/San Joaquin rivers and delta, the Sutter Buttes, and the Tulare Basin.
